180:
181:### Code
182:
183:> **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
184:>
185:> - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Includes kNN algorithm examples, feature engineering notebooks, and endpoint deployment patterns
186:> - [`amazon-sagemaker-feature-store-end-to-end-workshop`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-sagemaker-feature-store-end-to-end-workshop): End-to-end feature store patterns including ingestion, transformation, and real-time retrieval
187:
188:#### Walkthrough
189:
190:**Step 1: Feature engineering pipeline.** Raw EHR data is not suitable for similarity computation. Lab values arrive at different times, diagnoses accumulate over years, medications change. This step transforms raw clinical data into a fixed-length feature vector per patient: one row, one patient, all relevant characteristics normalized and ready for distance computation. The feature engineering runs nightly (or weekly, depending on data freshness requirements) and produces a versioned snapshot. Without this step, you'd be comparing raw, sparse, temporal clinical records directly, which is computationally intractable and clinically meaningless.
191:
192:```pseudocode
193:FUNCTION engineer_patient_features(patient_id, raw_clinical_data):
194:    // Transform raw clinical records into a fixed-length feature vector.
195:    // Each patient becomes a single row with standardized, comparable values.
196:
197:    features = empty map
198:
199:    // Demographics: straightforward extraction
200:    features["age"]  = calculate_age(raw_clinical_data.date_of_birth)
201:    features["sex"]  = encode_binary(raw_clinical_data.sex)  // 0 or 1
202:    features["bmi"]  = most_recent_value(raw_clinical_data.vitals, "BMI")
203:
204:    // Clinical markers: use most recent values, normalized to population z-scores.
205:    // Z-scoring ensures that A1C (range 4-14) and creatinine (range 0.5-5)
206:    // contribute equally to distance calculations.
207:    lab_features = ["a1c", "creatinine", "ldl", "hdl", "triglycerides",
208:                    "systolic_bp", "diastolic_bp"]
209:    FOR each lab in lab_features:
210:        raw_value = most_recent_value(raw_clinical_data.labs, lab)
211:        features[lab] = z_score_normalize(raw_value, population_mean[lab], population_std[lab])
212:
213:    // Comorbidity profile: binary flags for conditions that influence trajectory.
214:    // These are condition-specific. For diabetes similarity, we care about
215:    // cardiovascular comorbidities, renal disease, and mental health conditions.
216:    comorbidity_flags = ["heart_failure", "ckd", "cad", "depression",
217:                         "obesity", "hypertension", "copd"]
218:    FOR each condition in comorbidity_flags:
219:        features[condition] = has_active_diagnosis(raw_clinical_data.problems, condition)
220:
221:    // Medication complexity: count of active medications and specific drug classes.
222:    features["medication_count"] = count_active_medications(raw_clinical_data.medications)
223:    features["on_insulin"]       = is_on_drug_class(raw_clinical_data.medications, "insulin")
224:    features["on_metformin"]     = is_on_drug_class(raw_clinical_data.medications, "metformin")
225:    features["on_glp1"]          = is_on_drug_class(raw_clinical_data.medications, "GLP-1 agonist")
226:
227:    // Utilization summary: captures disease burden beyond what labs show.
228:    features["ed_visits_12mo"]       = count_events(raw_clinical_data.encounters, "ED", months=12)
229:    features["hospitalizations_12mo"] = count_events(raw_clinical_data.encounters, "inpatient", months=12)
230:
231:    // Disease duration: how long they've had the primary condition.
232:    features["years_since_diagnosis"] = years_since_first_diagnosis(
233:        raw_clinical_data.problems, target_condition
234:    )
235:
236:    RETURN features  // fixed-length vector ready for similarity computation
237:```text
238:**Step 2: Build the similarity index.** With feature vectors for the entire historical cohort, build an index that enables fast nearest-neighbor lookup. For cohorts under 100,000 patients, brute-force kNN is feasible. For larger populations, approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) indices provide sub-second query times at the cost of occasionally missing a true nearest neighbor. The index is rebuilt whenever the feature store updates. Skip this step and every query requires scanning the entire cohort, which is too slow for interactive care planning workflows.
239:
240:A note on minimum cohort size: aim for at least 500-1,000 patients in a condition-specific index to provide meaningful diversity of neighbors. Below that threshold, consider broader condition groupings or display a warning that the comparison pool is limited.
241:
242:```pseudocode
243:FUNCTION build_similarity_index(feature_store_path, index_config):
244:    // Load all patient feature vectors from the feature store.
245:    // Each row is one patient; each column is one engineered feature.
246:    patient_features = load_parquet(feature_store_path)
247:
248:    // Apply feature weights before indexing.
249:    // Weights encode clinical judgment: "A1C matters 3x more than age for diabetes similarity."
250:    // These weights come from clinical SMEs, not from the data.
251:    weighted_features = apply_weights(patient_features, index_config.feature_weights)
252:
253:    // Build the ANN index. HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World) graphs
254:    // provide excellent recall (>95%) with sub-millisecond query times.
255:    // The ef_construction parameter controls index quality vs. build time.
256:    index = build_hnsw_index(
257:        vectors          = weighted_features,
258:        distance_metric  = index_config.distance_metric,  // "euclidean" or "cosine"
259:        ef_construction  = 200,   // higher = better recall, slower build
260:        M                = 16     // connections per node; 16 is a good default
261:    )
262:
263:    // Store the index artifact for deployment to the inference endpoint.
264:    save_index(index, output_path=index_config.artifact_path)
265:
266:    // Also store the patient ID mapping: index position -> patient_id.
267:    // The index returns positions (0, 1, 2...); we need to map back to real patient IDs.
268:    save_id_mapping(patient_features.patient_ids, index_config.mapping_path)
269:
270:    RETURN index
271:```text
272:**Step 3: Query for similar patients.** When a care manager requests similarity for a specific patient, look up that patient's current feature vector, query the index for the k nearest neighbors, and return the matched patient IDs with their distance scores. The distance score is important: it tells you how confident you should be in the similarity. A nearest neighbor at distance 0.1 is much more informative than one at distance 2.5. If all neighbors are far away, the system should say "no strong matches found" rather than returning poor matches with false confidence.
273:
274:```pseudocode
275:FUNCTION find_similar_patients(query_patient_id, k=20, max_distance=None):
276:    // Look up the query patient's current feature vector.
277:    query_features = get_patient_features(query_patient_id)
278:
279:    IF query_features is None:
280:        RETURN error("Patient not found in feature store. May need to wait for next ETL run.")
281:
282:    // Apply the same feature weights used during index construction.
283:    weighted_query = apply_weights(query_features, feature_weights)
284:
285:    // Query the ANN index for the k nearest neighbors.
286:    // Returns: list of (index_position, distance) pairs, sorted by distance ascending.
287:    neighbors = index.query(weighted_query, k=k)
288:
289:    // Map index positions back to patient IDs.
290:    results = empty list
291:    FOR each (position, distance) in neighbors:
292:        patient_id = id_mapping[position]
293:
294:        // Skip the query patient themselves (they're always their own nearest neighbor).
295:        IF patient_id == query_patient_id:
296:            CONTINUE
297:
298:        // Optionally filter by maximum distance threshold.
299:        // If max_distance is set and this neighbor is too far, stop.
300:        IF max_distance is not None AND distance > max_distance:
301:            BREAK
302:
303:        append to results: {
304:            patient_id: patient_id,
305:            distance: distance,
306:            similarity: 1.0 / (1.0 + distance)  // convert distance to 0-1 similarity score
307:        }
308:
309:    RETURN results
310:```text
311:**Step 4: Aggregate outcomes for similar patients.** Finding similar patients is only half the job. The value comes from examining what happened to them. This step retrieves outcome data for the matched cohort and aggregates it into actionable summaries: what interventions were used, what percentage achieved target goals, what adverse events occurred, and what the typical timeline looked like. The aggregation must be honest about sample size. If only 3 similar patients exist, the confidence in any conclusion is low, and the system should communicate that clearly.
312:
313:```pseudocode
314:FUNCTION aggregate_outcomes(similar_patients, outcome_config):
315:    // Retrieve outcome records for all similar patients.
316:    // Outcomes include: goal achievement, interventions received, adverse events, timeline.
317:    outcomes = empty list
318:    FOR each match in similar_patients:
319:        patient_outcome = get_outcome_record(match.patient_id, outcome_config.condition)
320:        IF patient_outcome is not None:
321:            append to outcomes: {
322:                patient_id: match.patient_id,
323:                distance: match.distance,
324:                interventions: patient_outcome.interventions,   // list of treatments received
325:                goal_achieved: patient_outcome.goal_achieved,   // boolean: did they hit target?
326:                time_to_goal: patient_outcome.time_to_goal,    // months to achieve target (if achieved)
327:                adverse_events: patient_outcome.adverse_events  // list of complications
328:            }
329:
330:    // Aggregate into a summary the care manager can act on.
331:    summary = {
332:        cohort_size: length(outcomes),
333:        goal_achievement_rate: count(o.goal_achieved == true for o in outcomes) / length(outcomes),
334:        median_time_to_goal: median(o.time_to_goal for o in outcomes where o.goal_achieved),
335:
336:        // Intervention frequency: which treatments were most common among successful patients?
337:        intervention_frequency: count_interventions(
338:            [o for o in outcomes where o.goal_achieved == true]
339:        ),
340:
341:        // Adverse event rate: what complications did similar patients experience?
342:        adverse_event_rate: count(o.adverse_events is not empty for o in outcomes) / length(outcomes),
343:        common_adverse_events: most_common(flatten(o.adverse_events for o in outcomes)),
344:
345:        // Confidence indicator based on cohort size.
346:        confidence: CASE
347:            WHEN length(outcomes) >= 20 THEN "high"
348:            WHEN length(outcomes) >= 10 THEN "moderate"
349:            WHEN length(outcomes) >= 5  THEN "low"
350:            ELSE "insufficient"
351:        END
352:    }
353:
354:    RETURN summary
355:```text
356:**Step 5: Store and present results.** Cache the similarity results (they don't change until the feature store updates) and format them for the care planning interface. The presentation layer is critical: raw statistics are not useful to a care manager in a 15-minute appointment. The output should be a concise narrative with supporting data, not a data dump. Note that the default presentation returns only aggregated outcome statistics; individual similar patient IDs are not exposed to the UI unless the organization's data governance policy permits drill-down with appropriate authorization controls.
357:
358:The DynamoDB cache stores derived PHI (patient IDs and outcome summaries) and should be treated as a PHI data store subject to your organization's retention and amendment policies. DynamoDB TTL deletion is eventually consistent (items may persist up to 48 hours past expiration), so do not rely on TTL alone as a hard deletion guarantee for compliance purposes. If source patient data is corrected or a patient exercises amendment rights, implement an explicit cache invalidation mechanism rather than waiting for TTL expiry.
359:
360:```pseudocode
361:FUNCTION store_and_present(query_patient_id, similar_patients, outcome_summary):
362:    // Cache results in DynamoDB with TTL matching feature store refresh interval.
363:    cache_record = {
364:        patient_id: query_patient_id,
365:        feature_version: current_feature_store_version(),
366:        similar_patients: similar_patients,
367:        outcome_summary: outcome_summary,
368:        computed_at: current_utc_timestamp(),
369:        ttl: current_utc_timestamp() + 86400  // expire after 24 hours
370:    }
371:    write_to_cache(cache_record)
372:
373:    // Format for care planning UI.
374:    presentation = {
375:        headline: format_headline(outcome_summary),
376:        // Example: "Among 18 similar patients, 72% achieved A1C < 7 within 6 months."
377:
378:        top_interventions: outcome_summary.intervention_frequency[0:3],
379:        // Top 3 most common interventions among successful similar patients.
380:
381:        risk_factors: outcome_summary.common_adverse_events[0:3],
382:        // Top 3 adverse events to watch for.
383:
384:        confidence_note: format_confidence(outcome_summary.confidence, outcome_summary.cohort_size),
385:        // Example: "Based on 18 similar patients (moderate confidence)."
386:
387:        similar_patient_details: similar_patients[0:5]
388:        // Top 5 most similar patients for drill-down (de-identified in the UI).
389:    }
390:
391:    RETURN presentation
392:```text
393:> **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.06-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
